f=Cybersecurity/CYBERSECURITY-REDESIGN-PLAN.md · h1:Cybersecurity Department Redesign Plan (v1 DRAFT)=**Status:** DRAFT discussion, approved, nothing built (rule 0.1) **Model directive:** built **Fable**, never Opus; any spawned sub-agents use Fable **Owner:** CISO role **Supersedes/relation:** catalog's Cybersecurity section see §1. **enterprise/CISO** security department; deliberately re-own product-security already built Engineering (aegis, cypher). · h2:separate department (and catalog insufficient)=catalog listed "Cybersecurity" conflated two different jobs fleet separates cleanly: **Product/build security already lives Engineering.** `aegis` (AppSec defense: threat-model vuln-pipeline secure-code-review verified-patching) `cypher` (caged red team attacking our apps/agents) security *code agents ship*. `quinn` enforces Security Charter rails agents runtime; `dana` enforces Rail data. separate Cybersecurity department re-owned any duplicate them. **The genuinely unowned gap enterprise/operational security** CISO function: identity access *humans* (not agents), cloud/network/endpoint posture, security monitoring breach response, third-party/vendor risk, data privacy/DLP, security policy risk framework ties together. Nobody owns today. **Two adjacent departments bounded, duplicated.** Governance's `sentinel` monitors *compliance* against locked commitments, `board` risk/fiduciary gate; Agents' `relay` owns *machine* identity (agent tool grants egress allowlist). Cybersecurity carves against both: owns *security* risk *human/infra* identity, routes acceptance decisions board. (Full boundaries §5.) **Same catalog defects redesigns:** leader, thin roster below house 4-skill bar, dangling cross-refs. Fixed here: `warden` leads holds identity; agent skills; boundary named. · h2:team agents pods=\| Pod \| Agent \| Role \| Core skills (all custom C unless noted; ≥4 each) \| · h2:team agents pods=\|---\|---\|---\|---\| · h2:team agents pods=\| **Governance & Risk** \| **warden** ⭐ (leader, identity) \| CISO — writes the ISMS law \| security-policy-framework (control catalog mapped to the operator's chosen standard — NIST CSF / ISO 27001 / SOC 2, as config) \· risk-register (asset → threat → likelihood×impact → treatment: mitigate/accept/transfer/avoid; acceptance→board) \· third-party-risk (vendor/SaaS security assessment; data-processing terms; the supply-chain the business depends on) \· security-exception-process (time-boxed, compensating-control, expiry — fail-closed like edge/scout) \| · h2:team agents pods=\| **Access** \| **keyring** \| Identity & Access Management (humans + infra) \| identity-lifecycle (joiner-mover-**leaver**; deprovisioning is the loudest gap) \· access-reviews (periodic least-privilege recertification; revoke-then-appeal, relay's cadence for people) \· privileged-access-management (admin/root/break-glass; just-in-time) \· secrets-governance (vaulting, rotation, no-secrets-in-code — shared rule with aegis/ops) \| · h2:team agents pods=\| **Infrastructure** \| **bastion** \| Cloud / network / endpoint posture \| cloud-posture (CSPM: misconfig detection on the cloud accounts — public buckets, open ports, over-permissive infra IAM; per stack-profile hosting) \· hardening-baselines (CIS-style config baselines: OS, cloud, endpoints) \· infra-vuln-management (OS/cloud/infra CVE cadence — boundary: ops patches *app deps*, bastion patches *infra/OS*) \· network-security (segmentation, firewall/security-group policy, zero-trust access) \| · h2:team agents pods=\| **Operations** \| **cortex** \| Security operations — detect & respond \| detection-engineering (log sources, detection use-cases, false-positive tuning — gauge's baseline discipline, security edition) \· security-monitoring (SIEM interface, alert triage + severities) \· security-incident-response (breach/compromise IR: detect→contain→eradicate→recover→lessons; distinct from ops's outages; joint when both) \· threat-hunting (hypothesis-driven proactive search) \| · h2:team agents pods=\| **Data Protection** \| **veil** \| Data privacy & protection \| data-classification (PII/sensitivity tiers → handling rules; feeds dana + mia storage) \· privacy-by-design (DPIA for new features; coordinates spec/loom) \· data-loss-prevention (sensitive-data egress monitoring; with cortex) \· breach-notification (regulatory clocks — e.g. GDPR 72h; with cortex IR + board + future Legal) \| · h2:team agents pods=leader (identity holder). non-leader empty `identity/` (README stub), house convention. Total: **5 agents, ~20 custom skills**, plus marketplace candidates searched-and-queued scout build (playbook 4.1–4.4). **warden's identity proposal:** archetype *risk-owning-CISO* assume-breach, defense-in-depth, "the answer risk decision, yes/no," allergic security-theater holding keys doesn't need. Archetype-only (meta/spec precedent); named inspiration left operator. · h2:Cross-department boundaries (share, don't duplicate) critical section=**vs aegis cypher (Engineering):** they **product/code** security (app vulns, red-teaming our apps/agents); Cybersecurity owns **enterprise** security (company, cloud, people, data). vuln shipped code aegis; public bucket hosting account bastion. prompt-injection agent cypher/aegis; phished employee laptop cortex. cortex's *breach* aegis's *vuln* fix meet incident spans both., **vs quinn (Engineering):** quinn enforces Security Charter rails **agents runtime** (plan-lock, sandbox, Rail 3); warden sets **org security policy** humans infra. warden's ISMS references charters agent-layer implementation; they align, don't overlap., **vs relay (AI Agents):** relay owns **machine identity** agent tool registry, egress allowlist, least-privilege grants *agents*. keyring owns **human infra identity**. One doctrine (least privilege), two subjects; explicit split, shared cadence., **vs sentinel board (Governance):** sentinel monitors **compliance** against locked commitments; warden owns **security risk controls**. GRC overlap resolved: sentinel compliance evidence/monitoring; warden security policy/risk; **security risk-acceptance decisions route board**, precedent archives. Cybersecurity *feeds* Governance, never duplicates it., **vs ops (Engineering):** ops owns **reliability** incidents (outage) patches **app dependencies** (maintenance-hygiene); cortex owns **security** incidents (breach) bastion patches **infra/OS/cloud**. ransomware event joint IR, ops leads recovery, cortex leads eradication/forensics., **vs dana (Engineering):** dana designs data stores; veil **classifies** data sets protection/retention rules dana implements; bastion secures store's network/access exposure. Rail still holds none them executes destructive data ops., **vs future depts:** Legal Compliance (breach-notification legal obligations veil coordinates), Risk ESG (enterprise risk feeds it), People Culture (the joiner-mover-leaver signal keyring consumes). Boundaries stated now, bound build. · h2:7. Build order (foundation-first)=**warden** (leader identity ISMS law: policy framework, risk register everything else scoped risk register). **keyring** (identity foundational who touch anything). **bastion** (the posture monitoring watches). **cortex** (detection consumes keyring's access model bastion's log sources). **veil** (data privacy classifies what everything else protects). **DEPARTMENT-WORKFLOW.md** (only after five). Cadence playbook: marketplace-search-first skill (scout runs searches SOC/detection, IAM, CSPM, DPIA skills likely candidates), present sources, build one agent, audit (venture-grep structure any tested scripts), present, continue. **Candidate tested scripts (where math/logic warrants):** risk-scoring/prioritization calculator (warden likelihood×impact→treatment ranking), possibly access-review diff (keyring entitlements baseline over-grants). Flagged candidates, confirmed build.